What do you call a drug that brings a manufacturer at least $1 billion in revenue? A #blockbusterdrug. They're usually taken for long-term conditions like diabetes or high blood pressure. Eventually, their patent expires and cheaper generics can enter the market. #DefinedByBlink

It’s called “medication synchronization,” and it’s when your pharmacist aligns all of your prescription refills so you can pick them up at the same time — say, on the same day every month. Talk to your pharmacist to see how this could work for you. #ScriptTipTuesday

Hello Beelievers! 2 years ago, my co-founder @drjessicarx and I stood behind a retail pharmacy counter and couldn’t do the one thing we, as a pharmacist and pharmacy technician, were trained to do - help a patient. Because her insurance copay was so high, she couldn’t afford to pay for a simple generic medicine. This is not the healthcare we signed up for. Where insurance and middlemen profit off the sick and dictate the medicine we can take. So we started Honeybee, because drug prices should be straightforward and pharmacy should always be on the patient’s side - and 2019 showed us just how much America needs Honeybee. Thank you all for your love and support, we are super excited for what’s to come in 2020!

Prior Authorization (PA) is a decision that a health insurer makes saying if your prescription drug is medically necessary. Getting prior authorization isn't a promise your health insurance or plan will cover the cost and it usually takes one to two days (or longer) to obtain. #nowyouknow #goodrx #priorauthorization

You've heard the term "Drug Formulary" before, but maybe you don't know exactly what it means: It's a list of prescription drugs that an insurer covers and determines how much a patient will pay for his or her medication. A committee of physicians, nurse practitioners and pharmacists maintain the formulary and normally the drugs are grouped into separate tiers—or benefit categories—according to drug costs. #nowyouknow #goodrx #drugformulary
